data.content:
**In .NET 11, all your sync calls will throw at runtime — with no opt-in to restore them.**

In EF Core 10, the Cosmos DB provider let you opt into sync-over-async. **EF Core 11 fully removes that escape hatch.** `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` always throw when used with the Cosmos DB provider.

You must convert every method to async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- **No workaround** — the sync-over-async opt-in you had in .NET 10 is gone
- Callers of these methods must also be updated to `await` the results
- This is Cosmos-specific; the relational providers still support sync I/O

Tracking issue: [dotnet/efcore#37059](https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/issues/37059)
